###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#DissolvedOxygen
:DissolvedOxygen rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                          :Soluble ;
                 :EmpiricalFormula "O2" ;
                 :GujerNotation "S_O2" ;
                 rdfs:isDefinedBy "A dissolved gaseous oxygen component present in the liquid phase of wastewater treatment systems. Dissolved oxygen serves as the primary terminal electron acceptor for aerobic microorganisms and is essential for biological processes such as aerobic organic matter degradation, nitrification, and aerobic phosphorus removal. Dissolved oxygen concentration strongly influences microbial activity, reaction kinetics, treatment efficiency, and the operational performance of aerobic treatment processes." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#ElementalSulfur
:ElementalSulfur rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                          :Soluble ;
                 :EmpiricalFormula "S0" ;
                 :GujerNotation "S_S0" ;
                 rdfs:isDefinedBy "Elemental sulfur is an inorganic sulfur component with oxidation state zero. In wastewater treatment systems, it can occur as an intermediate in sulfur oxidation and reduction pathways and may be reduced by sulfur-reducing microorganisms." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#EndogenousResidue
:EndogenousResidue rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                            :MicroorganismBiomass ;
                   :EmpiricalFormula "CHyeOzeNaePbe" ;
                   :GujerNotation "X_U_Org" ;
                   rdfs:isDefinedBy "A particulate organic component representing biodegradable microbial residues and cellular materials released through endogenous decay, biomass lysis, and microbial metabolism in wastewater treatment systems. Endogenous residues contribute to sludge composition, particulate organic matter accumulation, substrate recycling, and subsequent degradation or stabilisation processes during biological wastewater treatment and sludge digestion." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#EvolutionOfCO2Gas
:EvolutionOfCO2Gas rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                            :CarbonRemovalProcess ;
                   :consumesSubstrate :Carbonate ,
                                      :HydrogenIon ;
                   :occursIn :AnaerobicBioreactor ;
                   :producesProduct :CarbonDioxide ;
                   :isDefinedBy "Evolution and release of dissolved inorganic carbon as carbon dioxide gas during wastewater treatment and anaerobic digestion processes." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#FermentableBiodegradableSolubleOrganics
:FermentableBiodegradableSolubleOrganics rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                  :Soluble ;
                                         :EmpiricalFormula "CHYfOZfNAfPBf" ;
                                         :GujerNotation "S_F" ;
                                         rdfs:isDefinedBy "A soluble biodegradable organic component consisting of readily fermentable dissolved organic matter present in wastewater treatment systems. Fermentable biodegradable soluble organics serve as substrates for fermentative microorganisms, supporting the production of volatile fatty acids, alcohols, hydrogen, and other intermediate compounds during anaerobic and anoxic biological processes such as fermentation, acetogenesis, sulfate reduction, and methanogenesis." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#FermentationOfFSO
:FermentationOfFSO rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                            :CarbonRemovalProcess ;
                   :consumesSubstrate :FermentableBiodegradableSolubleOrganics ,
                                      :HydrogenIon ;
                   :hasKineticParameter :DecayRate_AD ,
                                        :MaxGrowthRate_AD ;
                   :occursIn :AnaerobicBioreactor ;
                   :producesProduct :Ammonium ,
                                    :Carbonate ,
                                    :Hydrogen ,
                                    :Phosphate ,
                                    :VolatileFattyAcids ;
                   :usesElectronDonor :FermentableBiodegradableSolubleOrganics ;
                   :isDefinedBy "Anaerobic fermentation of fermentable soluble organics resulting in the production of volatile fatty acids, hydrogen, and acidogenic biomass during anaerobic wastewater treatment processes." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#Glucose
:Glucose rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                  :Soluble ;
         :EmpiricalFormula "C6H12O6" ;
         :GujerNotation "S_Glu" ;
         rdfs:isDefinedBy "A soluble biodegradable organic component commonly present in wastewater and utilised as a carbon and energy source by microorganisms during biological treatment processes. Glucose supports microbial growth and metabolism in processes such as aerobic respiration, fermentation, denitrification, sulfate reduction, and anaerobic digestion, contributing to organic matter degradation, biomass production, and carbon transformation within wastewater treatment systems." .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#Glycogen
:Glycogen rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                   :Soluble .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#GrowthOfAcetoclasticSRB
:GrowthOfAcetoclasticSRB rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                  :SulfurRemovalProcess ;
                         :consumesSubstrate :Acetate ,
                                            :Ammonium ,
                                            :Carbonate ,
                                            :Phosphate ,
                                            :Sulphate ,
                                            :VolatileFattyAcids ;
                         :hasKineticParameter :DecayRate_AS ,
                                              :H2SInhibition_AS ,
                                              :HalfSatCoeff_AS ,
                                              :HalfSatCoeff_N_AS ,
                                              :MaxGrowthRate_AS ;
                         :hasStoichiometricParameter :YieldCoeff_AS ;
                         :occursIn :AnaerobicBioreactor ;
                         :producesProduct :Carbonate ,
                                          :HydrogenIon ,
                                          :HydrogenSulfide ,
                                          :Water ;
                         :usesElectronAcceptor :Sulphate ;
                         :usesElectronDonor :Acetate ,
                                            :VolatileFattyAcids ;
                         :isDefinedBy "Growth of acetoclastic sulfate-reducing biomass through the anaerobic oxidation of acetate coupled with sulfate reduction, resulting in sulfide production and biomass formation in wastewater treatment systems." ;
                         rdfs:isDefinedBy """Growth of acetoclastic sulfate-reducing biomass is an anaerobic sulfur transformation process in which acetoclastic sulfate-reducing microorganisms use acetate-rich volatile fatty acids as electron donors while reducing sulfate (SO₄²⁻) to sulfide species.

This process links carbon degradation with sulfur reduction by converting organic substrates into carbonate species while producing hydrogen sulfide and new sulfate-reducing biomass. Acetoclastic sulfate reduction is important in sulfate-rich wastewater environments because it competes with acetoclastic methanogenesis for acetate and can influence methane production, sulfide accumulation, alkalinity, and overall anaerobic reactor performance.""" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#GrowthOfAcetogenicSRBBiomass
:GrowthOfAcetogenicSRBBiomass rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                       :SulfurRemovalProcess ;
                              :consumesSubstrate :Ammonium ,
                                                 :Carbonate ,
                                                 :HydrogenIon ,
                                                 :Phosphate ,
                                                 :Propionate ,
                                                 :Sulphate ;
                              :hasKineticParameter :DecayRate_ACS ,
                                                   :H2SInhibition_ACS ,
                                                   :HalfSatCoeff_ACS ,
                                                   :HalfSatCoeff_N_ACS ,
                                                   :MaxGrowthRate_ACS ;
                              :hasStoichiometricParameter :YieldCoeff_ACS ;
                              :occursIn :AnaerobicBioreactor ;
                              :producesProduct :Ammonium ,
                                               :Carbonate ,
                                               :Hydrogen ,
                                               :HydrogenIon ,
                                               :HydrogenSulfide ,
                                               :Phosphate ,
                                               :VolatileFattyAcids ,
                                               :Water ;
                              :usesElectronAcceptor :Sulphate ;
                              :usesElectronDonor :Propionate ;
                              :isDefinedBy "Growth of acetogenic sulfate-reducing biomass through the anaerobic degradation of proprionate coupled with sulfate reduction, resulting in sulfide production and biomass formation in wastewater treatment systems." ;
                              rdfs:isDefinedBy """Growth of acetogenic sulfate-reducing biomass is an anaerobic sulfur transformation process in which acetogenic sulfate-reducing microorganisms oxidise propionate and related organic substrates while reducing sulfate (SO₄²⁻) to sulfide species such as hydrogen sulfide (H₂S).

Propionate functions as the electron donor, while sulfate acts as the terminal electron acceptor. This process contributes to sulfur cycling, organic matter degradation, and sulfide production under anaerobic conditions. It is particularly relevant in saline and sulfate-rich wastewater systems, where sulfate-reducing microorganisms compete with methanogens for available electron donors and influence methane production, sulfide formation, and reactor stability.""" .


###  http://www.semanticweb.org/hope/ontologies/2026/3/WRRFs_Ontology2#GrowthOfHydrogenotrophicSRB
:GrowthOfHydrogenotrophicSRB rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                      :SulfurRemovalProcess ;
                             :consumesSubstrate :Ammonium ,
                                                :Carbonate ,
                                                :Hydrogen ,
                                                :Phosphate ,
                                                :Sulphate ;
                             :hasKineticParameter :DecayRate_HS ,
                                                  :H2SInhibition_HS ,
                                                  :HalfSatCoeff_HS ,
                                                  :HalfSatCoeff_N_HS ,
                                                  :MaxGrowthRate_HS ;
                             :hasStoichiometricParameter :YieldCoeff_HS ;
                             :occursIn :AnaerobicBioreactor ;
                             :producesProduct :HydrogenIon ,
                                              :HydrogenSulfide ,
                                              :Water ;
                             :usesElectronAcceptor :Sulphate ;
                             :usesElectronDonor :Hydrogen ;
                             :isDefinedBy "Growth of hydrogenotrophic sulfate-reducing biomass through the anaerobic oxidation of hydrogen coupled with sulfate reduction, resulting in sulfide production and biomass formation in wastewater treatment systems." ;
                             rdfs:isDefinedBy """Growth of hydrogenotrophic sulfate-reducing biomass is an anaerobic sulfur transformation process in which hydrogenotrophic sulfate-reducing microorganisms use hydrogen (H₂) as the electron donor and sulfate (SO₄²⁻) as the terminal electron acceptor to produce sulfide species and new biomass.

This process is significant in sulfate-rich anaerobic wastewater systems because it consumes hydrogen that may otherwise support hydrogenotrophic methanogenesis. By reducing sulfate to sulfide, hydrogenotrophic sulfate-reducing microorganisms contribute to sulfur cycling, influence methane production pathways, and affect sulfide accumulation, corrosion potential, odour formation, and process stability.""" .


